Most people think typography is about picking a font that screams "I have taste!" (Comic Sans, anyone?). But real typography is about making words so easy to read your users forget they're even reading. A boring font that's comfy to read beats a fancy font that makes people squint.

## The Readability Checklist

When text is easy to read, users just get the message. When it's hard, they work for it, and nobody signed up for that.

The five things that matter:

1. **Size** — Anything under 15px on the web is basically unreadable and exclusively for legal disclaimers. 16–18px is the comfort zone for body text.
2. **Line height** — Too tight and lines blur together. 1.6 or higher for body text.
3. **Line length** — 45–75 characters per line is ideal. Over 80 gets hard to follow. Under 40 feels choppy.
4. **Contrast** — Black on white is the standard. Don't go below 4.5:1 contrast for body text.
5. **Letter spacing** — Leave it alone for body text. For all-caps labels, add space.

